b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p9_nomenclature_polyatomic"\n    xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/"\n    xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"\n    xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Nomenclature for Ionic Compounds with Polyatomic Ions</title>\n        <objref idref="chemical_formulas"/>\n        <objref idref="name_compounds"/>\n    </head>\n    <body>\n\n        <p>The ions that we have discussed so far are called monatomic ions, that is, they are ions\n            formed from only one atom. We also find many <extra><anchor>polyatomic ions</anchor><meaning><material><p>ions composed of more than one atom</p></material></meaning></extra>. These ions, which act as\n            discrete units, are electrically charged molecules (a group of bonded atoms with an\n            overall charge). Some of the more important polyatomic ions are listed in Table.\n            Oxyanions are polyatomic ions that contain one or more oxygen atoms. At this point in\n            your study of chemistry, you should memorize the names, formulas, and charges of the\n            most common polyatomic ions. Because you will use them repeatedly, they will soon become\n            familiar.</p>\n        <table>\n            <tr>\n                <td align="center"><em style="bold">Name</em></td>\n                <td align="center"><em style="bold">Formula</em></td>\n                <td align="center"><em style="bold">Name</em></td>\n                <td align="center"><em style="bold">Formula</em></td>\n\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>ammonium</td>\n                <td>NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup></td>\n                <td>phosphate</td>\n                <td>PO<sub>4</sub><sup>3-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>peroxide</td>\n                <td>O<sub>2</sub><sup>2-</sup></td>\n                <td>hydrogen phosphate</td>\n                <td>HPO<sub>4</sub><sup>2-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>hydroxide</td>\n                <td>OH<sup>-</sup></td>\n                <td>dihydrogen phosphate</td>\n                <td>H<sub>2</sub>PO<sub>4</sub><sup>-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>acetate</td>\n                <td>C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>3</sub>O<sub>2</sub><sup>-</sup></td>\n                <td>perchlorate</td>\n                <td>ClO<sub>4</sub><sup>-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>cyanide</td>\n                <td>CN<sup>-</sup></td>\n                <td>chlorate</td>\n                <td>ClO<sub>3</sub><sup>-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>carbonate</td>\n                <td>CO<sub>3</sub><sup>2-</sup></td>\n                <td>chlorite</td>\n                <td>ClO<sub>2</sub><sup>-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>bicarbonate</td>\n                <td>HCO<sub>3</sub><sup>-</sup></td>\n                <td>hypochlorite</td>\n                <td>ClO<sup>-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>nitrate</td>\n                <td>NO<sub>3</sub><sup>-</sup></td>\n                <td>chromate</td>\n                <td>CrO<sub>4</sub><sup>2-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>nitrite</td>\n                <td>NO<sub>2</sub><sup>-</sup></td>\n                <td>dichromate</td>\n                <td>Cr<sub>2</sub>O<sub>7</sub><sup>2-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>sulfate</td>\n                <td>SO<sub>4</sub><sup>2-</sup></td>\n                <td>permanganate</td>\n                <td>MnO<sub>4</sub><sup>-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>hydrogen sulfate</td>\n                <td>HSO<sub>4</sub><sup>-</sup></td>\n                <td>oxalate</td>\n                <td>C<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub><sup>2-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>sulfite</td>\n                <td>SO<sub>3</sub><sup>2-</sup></td>\n                <td>thiosulfate</td>\n                <td>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub><sup>2-</sup></td>\n            </tr>\n\n        </table>\n        <p>Note that there is a system for naming some polyatomic ions; -ate and -ite are suffixes\n            designating polyatomic ions containing more or fewer oxygen atoms. Per- (short for\n            \xe2\x80\x9chyper\xe2\x80\x9d) and hypo- (meaning \xe2\x80\x9cunder\xe2\x80\x9d) are prefixes meaning more oxygen atoms than -ate\n            and fewer oxygen atoms than -ite, respectively. For example, perchlorate is\n                ClO<sub>4</sub><sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup>, chlorate is ClO<sub>3</sub><sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup>, chlorite is\n                ClO<sub>2</sub><sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup> and hypochlorite is ClO<sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup>. Unfortunately, the\n            number of oxygen atoms corresponding to a given suffix or prefix is not consistent; for\n            example, nitrate is NO<sub>3</sub>\xe2\x88\x92 while sulfate is SO<sub>4</sub><sup>2\xe2\x88\x92</sup>.</p>\n        <p>Many ionic compounds contain polyatomic ions as the cation, the anion, or both. As with\n            simple ionic compounds, these compounds must also be electrically neutral, so their\n            formulas can be predicted by treating the polyatomic ions as discrete units. We use\n            parentheses in a formula to indicate a group of atoms that behave as a unit. For\n            example, the formula for calcium phosphate, one of the minerals in our bones, is\n                Ca<sub>3</sub>(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>. This formula indicates that there are\n            three calcium ions (Ca<sup>2+</sup>) for every two phosphate\n                (PO<sub>4</sub><sup>3\xe2\x88\x92</sup>) groups. The PO<sub>4</sub><sup>3\xe2\x88\x92</sup> groups are\n            discrete units, each consisting of one phosphorus atom and four oxygen atoms, and having\n            an overall charge of 3\xe2\x88\x92. The compound is electrically neutral, and its formula shows a\n            total count of three Ca, two P, and eight O atoms.</p>\n        <p>We can apply the same steps as we saw earlier with addition of parenthesis where\n            necessary.</p>\n       \n       <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n        <dl>\n            <dt><em>Writing Chemical Formulas for an Ionic Compound</em></dt>\n            \n            <dd>\n               \n                <ol>\n                <li>Identify the cation and anion and their charges.</li>\n                <li>Combine the ions in the smallest whole number ratio such that the total number\n                    of positive charges is equal to the total number of negative charges.</li>\n                <li>Write the chemical formula that reflects this ratio.</li>\n            </ol></dd>\n        </dl>\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n        <example>\n            <p>Write the chemical formula for calcium nitrate.</p>\n            <ul>\n                <li>The two ions are Ca<sup>2+</sup> and NO<sub>3</sub><sup>-</sup>.</li>\n                <li>We can obtain the correct ratio by using the criss-cross method.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <image src="../webcontent/ion_ratio_cross.png" alt="Ca 2+ ion and NO3 - ions."/>\n            <p>The 2 becomes the subscript for the nitrate ion and the 1 becomes the subscript for\n                the calcium ion.</p>\n            <ul>\n                <li>The chemical formula is: <p><formula>Ca(NO<sub>3</sub>)<sub>2</sub></formula></p></li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Notice we use parenthesis around the NO<sub>3</sub>. To represent more than one of\n                the same polyatomic ion in a formula, you must use parenthesis.</p>\n        </example>\n        <example>\n            <p>Write the chemical formula for ammonium carbonate.</p>\n            <ul>\n                <li>The two ions are NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup> and\n                    CO<sub>3</sub><sup>2-</sup>.</li>\n                <li>We can obtain the correct ratio by using the criss-cross method.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <image src="../webcontent/ion_ratio_cross2.png"\n                alt="Symbol for ion of ammonium and symbol for ion of carbonate."/>\n            <ul>\n                <li>The chemical formula is: <p><formula>(NH<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>3</sub></formula></p></li>\n            </ul>\n        </example>\n          <wb:inline idref="polyatomic_formula_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline> \n        <section>\n            <title>Naming Ionic Compounds with Polyatomic Ions</title>\n            <body>\n                <p>We can also apply the general steps for naming ionic compounds to compounds with\n                    polyatomic ions.</p>\n                <dl>\n                    <dt><em>Naming Ionic Compounds</em></dt>\n                    <dd>\n                        <ol>\n                            <li>Name the cation first. \n                            <ul>\n                                <li>If the cation is monatomic, the name is the same as the element name.</li>\n                                <li>Include a roman numeral that indicates the charge of the ion for cations that can\n                                    have multiple charges.</li>\n                            </ul>\n                            </li>\n                            <li>Name the anion second.\n                            <ul>\n                                <li>If the anion is monatomic, change the ending of the element name to -ide.</li>\n                            </ul>\n                            </li>\n                        </ol>\n                    </dd>\n                </dl>\n                <formula>$$\\require{color}\\color[rgb]{0.5, 0.68, 0.42}\n                    \\underline{\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;}$$</formula>\n                \n                <p>It is helpful to note that there are not many positive polyatomic ions. You\'ll\n                    notice the only one on the list above is ammonium (NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>). When\n                    identifying the cation and anion in an ionic compound in most cases, with the\n                    exception of compounds containing ammonium, the first element is the cation and\n                    the rest of the formula represents the anion.</p>\n                <image src="../webcontent/potassium_acetate.png"\n                    alt="Formula for potassium acetate. Showing that K is the cation and C2H3O2 is the anion."/>\n                <p>We see in the example above the cation is potassium and the rest of the formula\n                        C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>3</sub>O<sub>2</sub> is the anion acetate. Giving the\n                    name: <em style="bold">potassium acetate</em></p>\n                <image src="../webcontent/barium_dichromate.png"\n                    alt="Formula for barium dichromate showing barium as the cation and the dichromate as the anion."/>\n                <p>In this example the cation is barium and the rest of the formula\n                        Cr<sub>2</sub>O<sub>7</sub> is the anion dichromate. Giving the name: <em\n                        style="bold">Barium dichromate</em></p>\n                  <wb:inline idref="polyatomic_name_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline> \n                <wb:inline idref="chem_form_digt" purpose="didigetthis"></wb:inline>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n            >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n            href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n            >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'